Tariff Submitter: Community Wind North, LLC FERC Tariff Program Name: FERC FPA Electric Tariff Tariff Title: Jurisdictional Agreement Tariff Record Proposed Effective Date: January 5, 2011 Tariff Record Title: Common Facilities, Operation and Revenue Sharing Agreement Option Code: A
FIRST AMENDED AND RESTATED COMMON FACILITIES, OPERATION AND REVENUE SHARING AGREEMENT
THIS FIRST AMENDED AND RESTATED COMMON FACILITIES, OPERATION AND REVENUE SHARING AND AGREEMENT (this "Agreement"), is entered into as of December 8, 2010 (the "Effective Date"), by and among the following Minnesota limited liability companies: Community Wind North, LLC ("CWN") North Community Turbines LLC ("NCT"), North Wind Turbines LLC ("NWT"), Community Wind North 1 LLC ("CWN 1"), Community Wind North 2 LLC, ("CWN 2") Community Wind North 3 LLC ("CWN 3"), Community Wind North 5 LLC ("CWN 5"), Community Wind North 6 LLC ("CWN 6"), Community Wind North 7 LLC ("CWN 7"), Community Wind North 8 LLC, ("CWN 8"), Community Wind North 9 LLC ("CWN 9"), Community Wind North 10 LLC, ("CWN 10"), Community Wind North 11 LLC ("CWN 11"), Community Wind North 13 LLC ("CWN 13") and Community Wind North 15 LLC ("CWN 15" and, together with CWN 1, CWN 2, CWN 5, CWN 6, CWN 7, CWN 8, CWN 9, CWN 10, CWN 11, CWN 13 and CWN 15, the "Turbine Companies" ). The parties hereto are sometimes referred to herein individually as a "Party" or "Project Company" and, collectively, as "Parties" or "Project Companies"). RECITALS 1. CWN was the original development vehicle for the proposed thirty (30) megawatt wind energy facility located near Verdi Township in Lincoln County, Minnesota (the "Project") and undertaken as a community-based energy development ("C-BED") project by 150 local Minnesota residents (the "Local Investors"), each of whom owned at the time 10% of one of the Turbine Companies. 2. CWN has (1) obtained key permits and governmental approvals for the Project (the "Governmental Approvals"); (2) is a party to an interconnection agreement with Northern States Power Company ("NSP") and Midwest Independent Transmission System Operator, Inc. to interconnect the Project at the Yankee Substation, which was filed with the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission under Docket No. ER09-1581-004 (the "Interconnection Agreement"); (3) entered into a substation lease and certain other real property documents for facilities that benefit the Project as a whole; (4) entered into a Balance of Plant Agreement (the "BOP Agreement") dated September 7, 2010 with Carstensen Contracting, Inc.; and (5) entered into an Operation and Maintenance Agreement with Edison Mission Operation and Maintenance, Inc. ("Operator") (the "O&M Agreement" and together with the Interconnection Agreement, the BOP Agreement, the PPAs, Turbine Agreements (as defined in the Amended and Restated Member Control and Operating Agreement of CWN dated as of September 27, 2010 (the "CWN LLC Agreement")), the Land Agreements and Grant Agreements (each as defined below), and any other agreements relating to the design, development, construction, and operation of the Project, each as amended, restated, modified or supplemented from time to time, the "Project Agreements"). 3. Each Turbine Company (i) is a party to a real property lease or easement agreement covering a parcel of land on which its wind turbine generator would be situated that would be part of a larger Project site (each, a "Land Agreement") and (ii) applied for and was
awarded a Renewable Energy/Energy Efficiency program grant through Rural Development, United States Department of Agriculture (the "USDA Grant") pursuant to a grant agreement (the "USDA Grant Agreement"). 4. CWN and the Local Investors identified Edison Mission Energy ("EME") as a potential co-owner and co-developer and entered into a term sheet with EME on July 8, 2008, as amended. 5. NCT and NWT were formed to enter into two C-BED Wind Generation Purchase Agreements each dated as of May 28, 2010 (the "PPAs") with NSP (in its capacity as power purchaser) for the sale of electric power and renewable energy credits generated by the Project. 6. In connection with the contemplated acquisition by Mission Community Wind North, Inc., a Delaware corporation ("Mission"), a wholly-owned subsidiary of EME, of an interest in the Project, a restructuring (the "Local Restructuring") of CWN, the Turbine Companies, NCT, NWT, and the Local Investors was undertaken for the future ease of administration of the Project and the Parties. 7. Since completion of the Local Restructuring, (1) CWN has owned 100% of each of NCT and NWT; (2) NCT has owned 100% of each of the outstanding membership interests of CWN 1, CWN 2, CWN 5, CWN 6, CWN 8 and CWN 15 (collectively, the "NCT Turbine Companies"), (3) NWT has owned 100% of the outstanding membership interests of CWN 3, CWN 7, CWN 9, CWN 10, CWN 11 and CWN 13 (collectively, the "NWT Turbine Companies"); and (3) the Local Investors have owned 100% of the outstanding membership interests of Norgaard Community Turbines LLC (the "Local HoldCo"). 8. Since consummation of the Membership Interest Purchase Agreement, dated as of September 27, 2010 ("MIPA"), among Mission, Local HoldCo, CWN, NCT, NWT and Community Energy Developers LLC, Mission has owned 99% of the financial rights and 49% of the governance rights in CWN and the Local HoldCo has owned 1% of the financial rights and 51% of the governance rights in CWN. 9. Pursuant to a Contract Administration and Agency Agreement by and among Mission, on the one hand and (i) each of NWT and the NWT Turbine Companies and (ii) each of NCT and the NCT Turbine Companies, on the other hand, Mission will administer the Turbine Agreements on behalf of the Project Companies. 10. Each Project Company directly or indirectly owns, leases and/or operates certain personal property, real property, fixtures, easements, equipment and facilities described in Exhibit A attached hereto (the "Shared Facilities") that are necessary for the operation and maintenance of the Project. 11. Each Party desires to grant to the other Parties the right to utilize the Shared Facilities on the terms and conditions set forth herein. 12. The Project Companies anticipate receiving revenues arising from (i) in the case of NCT and NWT, the sale of electric energy sold to NSP pursuant to the PPA to which it is a party and other amounts payable thereunder, including amounts in respect of network upgrades 2
and interconnection facilities, (ii) in the case each Turbine Company that receives USDA Grants, proceeds of such USDA Grants under which such Turbine Company is a grantee, which shall be used to acquire such Turbine Company's wind turbine generator, and (iii) distributions received from subsidiaries; and (iv) any other revenues, income, proceeds, grants, tax benefits or cash flow of any kind derived from ownership and operation of the Project and performance of the Project Agreements (collectively, the "Shared Revenues"). 2 13. In addition, each of the Project Companies is subject to certain obligations and liabilities under the Project Agreements and otherwise in connection with the construction, ownership and operation of the Project (collectively, the "Shared Liabilities"). 14. It is the intent of the Project Companies and the members of CWN that the Project be operated, and revenues and liabilities be shared, as if a single project company owned all of the assets of the Project and was party to all of the Project Agreements. 15. In light of the foregoing, the Parties and Community Wind North 4 LLC, Community Wind North 12 LLC and Community Wind North 14, each a Minnesota limited liability company and an indirect, wholly-owned subsidiary of CWN (collectively, the "Legacy Turbine Companies"), entered into a Common Facilities, Operations and Revenue Sharing Agreement, dated as of September 27, 2010 (the "Original Agreement"), pursuant to which NCT and NWT each granted to the other the right to share in (a) the Shared Revenues generated by such Party and its respective Turbine Companies and (b) the Shared Liabilities incurred by the other and its respective Turbine Companies, on the terms and conditions set forth therein. 16. The Legacy Turbine Companies initially held certain interests in the Project and the Shared Facilities but assigned such interests to certain Turbine Companies, and because the Legacy Turbine Companies hold no other assets or liabilities, CWN has elected to cause the Legacy Turbine Companies to be dissolved. 17. The Parties wish to amend and restate the Original Agreement to remove the Legacy Turbine Companies as parties thereto. NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the premises and of the mutual covenants and agreements contained herein, and for other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged, the Parties hereby agree as follows: AGREEMENT 1. TERM; EARLY TERMINATION 1.1 Term: The term of this Agreement shall commence on the Effective Date and shall continue in effect until terminated (a) by mutual agreement of the Parties or (b) pursuant to Section 1.2 of this Agreement. 1.2 Early Termination: This Agreement shall automatically terminate, without further action by either Party and without further liability of one Party to the other, upon the date that the Project has permanently ceased operation for the production of electric energy. 3 2. GRANT OF SHARED FACILITIES RIGHTS, REVENUES, AND OBLIGATIONS 2.1 Grant of Shared Facilities Rights: Subject to Section 3.1 and Section 3.3, each Project Company hereby grants to the other Project Companies, during the term of this Agreement, and on the terms and subject to the conditions hereof, the non-exclusive right to access and utilize the Shared Facilities as may be reasonably necessary in connection with the Parties' collective ownership, operation and maintenance of the Project as a whole. 2.2 Grant of Shared Revenues: Subject to Section 3.1 and Section 3.3, (i) each of the NCT Turbine Companies agrees to distribute its Shared Revenues to NCT and each of the NWT Turbine Companies agrees to distribute its Shared Revenues to NWT; and (ii) each of NCT and NWT hereby grants to the other, during the term of this Agreement, and on the terms and subject to the conditions hereof, the right to receive fifty percent (50%) of the Shared Revenues and agrees that all such Shared Revenues shall be distributed to CWN and allocated in accordance with the CWN LLC Agreement. 2.3 Assumption of Shared Liabilities: Subject to Section 3.1 and Section 3.3, each of the Project Companies hereby agree that the Shared Liabilities shall be shared among all of the Project Companies equally as if CWN were the single project company owning all of the assets (including the leasehold interests created by the Land Agreements). 2.4 Vesting: The right to access and utilize the Shared Facilities granted to each Party hereunder shall vest in such Party as a contracting party hereunder without any transfer of title or leasehold interest in the Shared Facilities. 3. NATURE OF SHARED FACILITIES RIGHTS 3.1 Limitation on Grant: Subject to Section 3.3, each Party's grant of rights to the other Party under Section 2.1 is made only to the extent that such grant does not limit in any material respect the ability of the granting Party to perform its obligations under any agreement to which it is or becomes a party, as the same may be hereafter modified or amended. 3.2 Assignment or Transfer: Except as set forth in Section 7.7, neither Party shall assign the rights granted to such Party hereunder or grant any permission, license, right of way or similar right to such rights granted hereunder without the prior written consent of the other Party. 3.3 Interference: In no event shall either Party be entitled to exercise its rights to access and utilize the Shared Facilities if the exercise of such rights would materially interfere with or limit the reasonable and necessary access and utilization of the Shared Facilities by the other Party. 3.4 Prior Written Consent: Neither Party shall take any action that results in the forbearance, foreclosure, termination or alteration of the other Party's access to, utilization of or reliance upon the Shared Facilities without the prior written consent of such other Party. 4 3.5 Essential Nature: Each Party hereby acknowledges that the other Party's rights to utilize the Shared Facilities are essential to the operation and maintenance of such other Party's Project. Each Party agrees that the Shared Facilities and the Projects shall be operated and maintained as if it formed a single, integrated wind-powered electric generating facility 4. OPERATION AND MAINTENANCE OF SHARED FACILITIES 4.1 Allocation of Certain Costs and Expenses: CWN shall utilize the Shared Revenues to pay (i) the costs of ownership or possession, operation, inspection, maintenance, repair, alteration, relocation, improvement and replacement of the Shared Facilities, which shall be operated and maintained by the Operator under the O&M Agreement and (ii) all other costs, including costs under the Project Agreements, associated with the construction, permitting, ownership and operation of the Project. 5. MATERIAL BREACH 5.1 Material Breach. In the event of any material breach of this Agreement by either Party and such breaching Party's failure to cure such material breach within a reasonable time not to exceed thirty (30) days after receipt of written notice from the other Party describing such breach, the notifying Party shall have the right in its sole discretion, in addition to all remedies available to the notifying Party at law or in equity, to (i) cure the breach on behalf of the breaching Party, (ii) suspend the breaching Party's access to the Shared Facilities for so long as such material breach shall be continuing and remain uncured, or (iii) terminate this Agreement. For the avoidance of doubt, the remedy specified in clause (i) may be exercised, without prejudice to any right or remedy of the notifying Party hereunder, by any lender of the notifying Party. If the notifying Party (or any lender thereof) chooses to cure the breaching Party's material breach, the breaching Party shall reimburse the notifying Party (or such lender) upon demand for all commercially reasonable costs incurred by the notifying Party in curing such material breach.
5 6. FORCE MAJEURE 6.1 Force Majeure. In the event of any occurrence or event (or combination of same) that is (a) beyond the reasonable control of, (b) without the fault or negligence of, and (c) not the direct or indirect result of a breach of this Agreement by, a Party that, in any case, could not have been avoided or overcome by such Party (or its subcontractors) through reasonably prudent action, which event or occurrence prevents or delays such Party in its performance of all (or part) of its obligations under this Agreement (each a "Force Majeure Event"), including without limitation, any act of God, government order or restraint, war (declared or undeclared) or warlike conditions, act of terrorism, blockade, revolution, strike, lockout, civil commotion, fire, flood, storm, epidemic or any other occurrence beyond a Party's reasonable control, such Party shall promptly notify the other Party thereof and, so long as such condition shall persist, such Party shall not be liable for such failure to perform or delay in performing its obligations (other than obligations for payment of amounts due hereunder) under this Agreement caused directly or indirectly thereby. The claiming Party shall give the other Party notice describing the particulars of the Force Majeure Event. Within fifteen (15) days after giving notice of the Force Majeure Event, the claiming Party shall give the other Party an estimate of the Force Majeure Event's expected duration and probable impact. The claiming Party shall continue to furnish the other Party with timely regular reports during the continuation of the Force Majeure Event. Each Party shall immediately exercise commercially reasonable efforts to mitigate or limit the impact to its obligations hereunder as a result of the Force Majeure Event. 7. MISCELLANEOUS 7.1 Agreement to Cooperate. Each Party agrees to reasonably cooperate with the other Party so that, subject to the terms of this Agreement, each Party benefits from the full utilization and enjoyment of the Shared Facilities as is necessary for the efficient operation of the Project 7.2 Non-Interference. Subject to Section 3.3, each Party agrees not to interfere with the reasonable and necessary utilization of the Shared Facilities by the other Party as permitted hereunder. 7.3 Modification and Amendment. The terms of this Agreement may only be modified or amended in a writing signed by all of the Parties. 7.4 Waiver. The failure of a Party to insist upon or enforce strict performance of any of the provisions of this Agreement or to exercise any rights or remedies under this Agreement shall not be construed as a waiver or relinquishment to any extent of such Party's right to assert or rely upon any such provisions, rights, and remedies in that or any other instance; rather, the same shall be and remain in full force and effect. 7.5 Enforceability. Any provision of this Agreement which is prohibited or unenforceable in any jurisdiction shall, as to such jurisdiction, be ineffective only to the extent of such prohibition, but shall be effective to the extent of such remaining provisions hereof. 6 7.6 Transfer of Shared Facilities. Except as set forth in Section 7.7, neither Party may transfer, sell, assign or sub-lease its ownership interest in the Shared Facilities or any portion thereof without the prior written consent of the other Party. 7.7 Assignment. Neither Party may assign its rights or obligations hereunder without the prior written consent of the other Party, provided that either Party may collaterally assign this Agreement to any entity, or such entity's agent, in connection with a financing or a refinancing of such Party's Project. 7.8 Governing Law. This Agreement shall be governed by and constructed in accordance with the laws of the State of Minnesota, without regard to its conflict of laws provisions. 7.9 Inspection of Records. Each Party shall have access to any records concerning the Shared Facilities held by the other Party upon reasonable notice and at reasonable times. 7.10 Notices. All notices required or permitted to be given under this Agreement shall be in writing and shall be deemed to be duly given when personally delivered by a commercial messenger service, supported by a receipt of delivery, or when delivered by facsimile transmission supported by receipt. Notices to a Party shall be delivered to the attention of such Party at the following addresses:
1404 South Street Pipestone, MN 56164 Attn: Station Manager Tel: 507-562-2126
With copies to: Mission Community Wind North, Inc. 18101 Von Karman Avenue, Suite 1700 Irvine, CA 92612 Attention: Commercial Management Tel.: (949) 798-7897 Mission Community Wind North, Inc. 18101 Von Karman Ave., Suite 1700 Irvine, CA 92612 Attention: General Counsel Tel.: (949) 798-7908 7.11 Entire Agreement. This Agreement constitutes the entire agreement between the Parties, and all prior agreements, including, without limitation, the Original Agreement, pertaining to the subject matter hereof are superseded hereby.
7 7.12 Section Headings. The section headings in this Agreement are for convenience of reference only and shall not modify, define, expand, or limit any of the terms or provisions hereof. 7.13 Counterparts. This Agreement may be executed in one or more counterparts, each of which when so executed shall be deemed an original, and all of which when taken together shall constitute one and the same instrument.
